UNALLOCATED PENSION AND OTHER POSTRETIREMENT EXPENSE REPRESENTS THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN COSTS RECOGNIZED UNDER GENERALLY ACCEPTED ACCOUNTING PRINCIPLES IN THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA (GAAP) IN THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS AND FEDERAL COST ACCOUNTING STANDARDS REQUIRED TO BE UTILIZED BY OUR BUSINESS SEGMENTS FOR U.S. GOVERNMENT CONTRACTING PURPOSES. WE RECORDED NET PERIODIC BENEFIT COST RELATED TO PENSIONS AND OTHER POSTRETIREMENT BENEFITS OF

$3,383 MILLION

,

$3,127 MILLION

AND

$1,864 MILLION

IN

2012, 2011 AND 2010

, RESPECTIVELY. THE INCREASE IN NET PERIODIC BENEFIT COSTS RELATED TO PENSIONS AND OTHER POSTRETIREMENT BENEFITS IS PRIMARILY DUE TO HIGHER AMORTIZATION OF ACTUARIAL LOSSES AND HIGHER SERVICE COSTS DRIVEN BY LOWER DISCOUNT RATES. NOT ALL NET PERIODIC BENEFIT COST IS RECOGNIZED IN EARNINGS IN THE PERIOD INCURRED BECAUSE IT IS ALLOCATED TO PRODUCTION AS PRODUCT COSTS AND A PORTION REMAINS IN INVENTORY AT THE END OF THE REPORTING PERIOD. A PORTION OF PENSION AND OTHER POSTRETIREMENT EXPENSE IS RECORDED IN THE BUSINESS SEGMENTS AND THE REMAINDER IS INCLUDED IN UNALLOCATED PENSION AND OTHER POSTRETIREMENT EXPENSE. THE UNALLOCATED EXPENSE IN 2011 INCLUDES $161 MILLION OF ADDITIONAL EXPENSE RECORDED DURING THE THIRD QUARTER DUE TO AN ADJUSTMENT PRIMARILY RELATED TO PRIOR YEARS’ ACCUMULATED POSTRETIREMENT BENEFIT OBLIGATIONS. SEE THE DISCUSSION OF THE POSTRETIREMENT LIABILITIES IN NOTE

